To solve this problem, we can use the bubble sort algorithm to sort the list in descending order. We will iterate over the list multiple times, comparing each element with its adjacent element and swapping them if necessary. 

Here's the implementation of the function:

```python
def sort_list(lst):
    # Sort numbers in descending order
    for i in range(len(lst) - 1):
        for j in range(len(lst) - i - 1):
            if isinstance(lst[j], (int, float)) and isinstance(lst[j + 1], (int, float)):
                if lst[j] < lst[j + 1]:
                    lst[j], lst[j + 1] = lst[j + 1], lst[j]

    # Sort strings in alphabetical order
    for i in range(len(lst) - 1):
        for j in range(len(lst) - i - 1):
            if isinstance(lst[j], str) and isinstance(lst[j + 1], str):
                if lst[j] > lst[j + 1]:
                    lst[j], lst[j + 1] = lst[j + 1], lst[j]

    # Sort nested lists based on the sum of their elements
    for i in range(len(lst) - 1):
        for j in range(len(lst) - i - 1):
            if isinstance(lst[j], list) and isinstance(lst[j + 1], list):
                if sum(lst[j]) < sum(lst[j + 1]):
                    lst[j], lst[j + 1] = lst[j + 1], lst[j]

    return lst
```

