Inside the while loop, it calculates the mid index using bitwise operations to avoid using division. Then, it checks if the mid element is equal to the target. If it is, it updates the result variable to store the index of the first occurrence and moves the right pointer to the left to continue searching for earlier occurrences. 

If the mid element is greater than the target, it means the target can only be found in the left half of the array. In this case, the right pointer is moved to the left. 

If the mid element is less than the target, it means the target can only be found in the right half of the array. In this case, the left pointer is moved to the right.

The program continues this process until the left and right pointers meet or cross each other. Finally, it returns the result, which will contain the index of the first occurrence of the target element in the array or -1 if the target element is not present.

